d of dead weight or out of date teachers and staff. in a perfect world, it would be great but the human factor and greed get in the way. Not to mention the safety factor. I taught in both private and public schools in a large urban area and after struggling to teach in the public school, i jumped to a private schools where kids wanted to learn. I am not saying that all public schools are bad but each area and situation should be judged on its own merit. My grandkids go to a great public school but now there is the problem of helicopter parents who won't leave the teachers to teach!!! So if tis makes me a &quot;bad&quot; parent or teacher so be it but this is not Plato's perfect world! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="991" language="en" documentId="4024" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="smart grandma" date="Aug 29, 2013 5:59PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="9" thumbsDown="0" origId="4024" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="991"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>